{
  "text": "where X is a matrix of exogenous determinants of the riskiness of banks and \u03b3 is a vector of parameters to be estimated. The coefficients for a 1 and a 2 estimated using this equation differ only slightly from those estimated using Equation (1). Moreover, the introduction of exogenous control variables does not reduce the explanatory power of CP 1. Thus, the results in the last section does not depend on including the matrix of control variables X. [CITATION_1] suggest that macroeconomic factors as the government's fiscal position, the rate of inflation and the short-term real interest rate may have effects on the quality of bank assets. Column (1) in Table C .6 shows the regression results when X contains the short-term real interest rate. Its coefficient has a positive sign, suggesting that higher real interest rates make it harder for borrowers to honor their loans, but it is not significant. Similar results are obtained when controlling for the government's fiscal deficit as a percentage of the gross domestic product, the rate of inflation, the rate of growth of the gross domestic product and the gross domestic product per capita.",
